<BaseLayout
  title="Prevention Specialists"
  description="Credentialed prevention specialists can adapt the CSAP strategies and the SPF they already use for substance misuse to address problem gambling — no separate framework required."
>
  <header class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="page-header__eyebrow">
        <a href="/professionals">← Professionals</a>
      </p>
      <h1>Prevention Specialists</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        You already have the framework. Problem gambling fits the same CSAP
        strategies, the same Strategic Prevention Framework, and the same risk
        and protective factors you use for substance misuse — you do not have to
        reinvent the wheel.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>Why this fits the work you already do</h2>
      <p>
        Federal prevention infrastructure was built for alcohol and other drugs.
        Congress wrote the six prevention strategy categories into law in 1981,
        and the Center for Substance Abuse Prevention (CSAP) has organized the
        field around them ever since. Problem gambling never got a parallel
        build-out — no separate institute, no separate block grant, no separate
        framework. So the field adopted the infrastructure already standing. The
        six strategies are our strategies because they are the ones that exist.
      </p>
      <p>
        That is good news for prevention specialists: the credential you hold and
        the tools you already use transfer directly. In most cases, adding
        problem gambling is not a new program — it is one or two deliberate
        additions to work that is already running.
      </p>

      <h2>The case for shared risk and protective factors</h2>
      <p>
        Many of the factors that drive substance misuse also drive gambling harm.
        A single factor can predict multiple outcomes — substance use, mental
        health problems, and gambling alike. This is the shared risk and
        protective factor (SRPF) approach, and it is why cross-cutting prevention
        works. Across the social-ecological model, the overlap is consistent:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Individual:</strong> early first use or early first wager,
          impulsivity and sensation-seeking, co-occurring depression, anxiety, or
          ADHD, trauma and adverse childhood experiences.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Relationship:</strong> low parental monitoring, the behavior
          normalized in the home, pro-use or pro-betting peer norms, family
          conflict and weak family bonds.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Community:</strong> high density of outlets or betting venues,
          targeted local marketing, weak school climate, limited prosocial
          activities, neighborhood disorganization.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Societal:</strong> regulatory and pricing gaps, advertising
          volume and placement, a cultural narrative that the behavior is normal
          or harmless, economic precarity, and stigma that delays help-seeking.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        When you address a shared factor, you are very often preventing more than
        one harm at once.
      </p>

      <h2>The six CSAP strategies, applied to problem gambling</h2>
      <p>
        Each strategy you already use has a low-lift gambling adaptation:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Information Dissemination:</strong> add Problem Gambling
          Awareness Month messaging and helpline cards at venues, lottery
          retailers, and sportsbooks alongside your existing campaigns.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Prevention Education:</strong> add probability, marketing
          literacy, and personal-risk content to the skill-based curricula you
          already deliver.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Alternatives:</strong> offer no-stakes game nights and
          recovery-oriented activities that build the same protective factors.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Problem Identification &amp; Referral:</strong> add a brief
          gambling screen and a warm referral to the helpline. This is screening
          and referral — not diagnosis or treatment.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Community-Based Process:</strong> stand up a problem gambling
          sub-committee inside an existing substance use coalition.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Environmental:</strong> use the CAMP pillars — community norms,
          access &amp; availability, media messages, and policy &amp; enforcement
          — to change the conditions everyone moves through.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Work it through your domains</h2>
      <p>
        The guidance here is organized by the IC&amp;RC Prevention Specialist
        domains, so it maps to the certification and the day-to-day work:
      </p>
      <ul class="card-grid">
        {
          domains.map((d) => (
            <li>
              <a class="card-link" href={d.href}>
                <span class="card-link__title">{d.title}</span>
                <span>{d.body}</span>
              </a>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>


      <div class="sources">
        <h2>Learn more</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <a href="https://pttcnetwork.org/">
              Prevention Technology Transfer Center (PTTC) — the six CSAP strategies
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="https://www.samhsa.gov/substance-use/prevention">
              SAMHSA — Center for Substance Abuse Prevention and the Strategic Prevention Framework
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="https://internationalcredentialing.org/">
              IC&amp;RC — Prevention Specialist credential
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a href="https://www.ncpgambling.org/">
              National Council on Problem Gambling
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
